{{Infobox Korean name|hangul=삼성혈|hanja={{linktext|三|姓|穴}}|rr=Samseonghyeol|mr=Samsŏnghyŏl}} [[File:Three sacred holes in Jeju.JPG||thumb]] The '''Samseonghyeol''' ([[Korean language|Korean]] for “three clans' holes”) are three large holes in the ground in [[Jeju, Jeju|Jeju]] on [[Jeju-do|Jejudo]], an island in the northern [[East China Sea]]. The holes are in the city's urban area on the central north coast.
== Geology == {{Empty section|date=June 2008}}
== Legend == {{main article|Samseong mythology}}
According to legend, here three demigods emerged from the ground to become the founding fathers of [[Tamna]] and its people, whose descendants bear their family names: * Go Eulna ({{lang|ko-Hang|고을나}} = {{lang|ko-Hant|高乙那}}) * Ryang Eulna ({{lang|ko-Hang|량을나}} = {{lang|ko-Hant|良乙那}}) * Bu Eulna ({{lang|ko-Hang|부을나}} = {{lang|ko-Hant|夫乙那}})
According to an animated film shown at a local shrine, a mysterious man later arrived by ship bringing three beautiful princesses who became their wives, taught them agriculture, and helped them to develop and populate the island. Eventually the three men shot three arrows from the top of a mountain which landed in three places on the island, signifying the places of residence for their descendants.
== References == * [http://korean.go.kr/06_new/dic/search.jsp?att1=삼성혈 {{lang|ko-Hang|표준국어대사전}}]
